Description: 3-DAY ADVANCE NOTICE OF EX PARTE COMMUNICATION OF THE BIOENERGY ASSOCIATION OF CALIFORNIA,  CALIFORNIA FORESTRY ASSOCIATION, PHOENIX ENERGY, AND WEST BIOFUELS Pursuant to Rule 8.2 of Commissions Rules of Practice and Procedure, the Bioenergy Association of California (BAC), California Forestry Association (CalForests), Phoenix Energy, and West Biofuels hereby give 3 days advance notice  of an ex parte communication to take place in this Rulemaking.  The communication will be a meeting to take place at 8:30am on June 17, 2025, via WebEx.  The meeting participants will include Ms. Audrey Neuman (Advisor to Commissioner Houck), Julia Levin (Executive Director of BAC), Matt Dias   (President of CalForests), Mackenzie Castruita (Business Manager for West Biofuels), Greg Stangl (CEO of Phoenix Energy), and Nick Blair (Senior Policy Advocate for the Association of California Water Agencies).  The Association of California Water Agencies is not a party   to this Rulemaking.  The purpose of the meeting is to discuss the need to extend the BioMAT program.

NOTICE OF EX PARTE COMMUNICATION OF CALPINE CORPORATION  Pursuant to Rule 8.4 of the California Public Utilities Commission (“Commission”) Rules of Practice and Procedure, Calpine Corporation (“Calpine”) hereby gives timely notice of the ex parte meeting.   On January 9, 2023, Calpine’s attendees Matt Barmack, Vice President, Market & Regulatory Analysis; Avis Kowalewski, Vice President, Government & Regulatory Affairs; Joe Greco, Director, Strategic Origination; and Emily Turkel, Analyst, Government & Regulatory Affairs met with Jaime Rose Gannon, advisor to President Alice Busching Reynolds, over Webex from approximately 3:30 p.m. to 4:00 p.m.

ADVANCE THREE-DAY NOTICE OF EX PARTE COMMUNICATION OF CALPINE CORPORATION Pursuant to Article 8 of the California Public Utilities Commission (“Commission”) Rules of Practice and Procedure Calpine Corporation (“Calpine”) hereby files this three-day advance notice of the upcoming ex parte meeting.   Calpine has requested and had been granted an ex parte Webex meeting on January 9, 2023, from approximately 3:30 p.m. to 4:00 p.m. with Jaime Rose Gannon, advisor to President Alice Busching Reynolds. The purpose of the meeting is to discuss constraints and opportunities for additional geothermal operational flexibility.  Calpine’s tentative list of attendees is:  Matt Barmack, Vice President, Market & Regulatory Analysis; Avis Kowalewski, Vice President, Government & Regulatory Affairs; Joe Greco, Director, Strategic Origination; and Emily Turkel, Analyst, Government & Regulatory Affairs

Description: JOINT NOTICE OF EX PARTE COMMUNICATION OF THE BIOENERGY ASSOCIATION OF CALIFORNIA, CALIFORNIA ASSOCIATION OF SANITATION AGENCIES, MICROGRID RESOURCES COALITION, PLACER COUNTY AIR POLLUTION CONTROL DISTRICT, AND RURAL COUNTY REPRESENTATIVES OF CALIFORNIA Pursuant to Rule 8.2 of Commission’s Rules of Practice and Procedure, the Bioenergy Association of California (BAC), California Association of Sanitation Agencies (CASA), Microgrid Resources Coalition (MRC), Placer County Air Pollution Control District (PCAPCD”), and the Rural County Representatives of California (RCRC) hereby give notice of an ex parte communication in this Rulemaking. The communication consisted of a meeting with Commissioner Rechtschaffen’s staff via WebEx at 2pm on October 24, 2022. MOTION TO FURTHER UPDATE ITS 2018 RENEWABLES PORTFOLIO STANDARD PROCUREMENT PLAN

SUMMARY:  On October 30,2018, Steven Kelly, Policy Director for Independent Energy Producers Association (IEP), and Brian Cragg, outside counsel to IEP, met with Sandy Goldberg, advisor to Cmmr. Rechtschaffen, in San Francisco. Mr. Kelly reiterated the points made in IEP's comments on the 2018 Renewables Portfolio Standard (RPS) procurement plans, filed on September 21,2018. Mr. Kelly observed that the revised RPS procurement plans filed by load-serving entities in response to the enactment of Senate Bill 100 did not reveal a significant change in procurement and would not result in the procurement of new renewable energy resources needed by 2030. Mr. Kelly explained that to avoid a boom-or-bust cycle for procurement of renewable energy from new resources, the Commission should exercise the authority the Legislature granted it in Public Utilities Code Section 399.15(bX3) and increase the RPS requirement for LSEs above the statutory minimum. Mr. Cragg observed that an increased RPS level would also mesh with the state's efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emission levels by 2030. Mr. Kelly and Mr. Cragg also discussed the issues raised by proposals for a procurement entity. Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

Filed By: The American Wind Energy Association California Caucus
Description: SUMMARY:  On October 4, 2018, Brian Biering, Counsel, and Danielle Mills, Director, of of the the American Wind Energy Association (AWEA) California Caucus (ACC), and Johnny Casana of Pattern Energy, Scott Farris of EDP Renewables, and Virinder Singh of EDF Renewable Energy, as participating representative member companies, had a telephonic ex parte communication with Jennifer Kalafut and Ehren Seybert, advisors to Cmmr. Peterman. ACC members discussed integration between the Integrated Resource Planning and Renewable Portfolio Standard proceedings and recommended that the interaction between the procurement and transmission planning process needs to be a coordinated effort between the Commission and the California Independent System Operator with clear direction from both moving forward. ACC Members stressed the importance of timing in the current procurement cycle. ACC members also discussed the fleeting opportunity to obtain low-cost sources of renewable energy with the federal production tax credit (PTC) set to expire. ACC Members discussed the levelized cost of wind, both with and without the PTC, and how individual Load-Serving Entities reflect the value of PTC-eligible wind.
